<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Housing Standards Review</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> by Sustainable Homes</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Overview</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The regulations and stand</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ards established by national Government are a key means of raising the environmental performance of new housing and improving people’s local quality of life.  Sustainable Homes welcomes this opportunity to contribute to the continuing review of housing standards.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As the leading provider of training, research, consultancy and benchmarking for social housing providers in the environmental performance of new and existing homes we have both expert and practical experience</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to inform the review. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our response also draws on the experience </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SHIFT (Sustainable Homes Index for Tomorrow)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> benchmarking and good practice network </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with a membership of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> over 60 housing associations.  Together these manage over one million homes with over two million residents. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We welcome the proposals to rationalise and simplify the confused approach to housing standards and reduce the volume of guidance.  We also welcome the intention to clarify the distinctive contribution of building regulations and planning policy/guidance.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe that alongside this need for efficiency policy makers must maintain an awareness of the limits of market self-regulation and the unique position of government in the management of environmental risks. This concern was strongly stated in a 2010 review by the Innovation and Growth Team: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“Primary leadership needs to come from Government, because of the degree of market failure and because plans for carbon reduction must reach into every fibre of the built environment, at a scale that is far beyond the reach of anybody other than Government.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have identified a number of important areas that the consultation and its accompanying impact assessment have failed to address.  These are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">covered</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in current standards and risk being lost.  Many contribute significantly to the achievement of important wider environmental, social and health outcomes.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A Sustainable Homes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (2013)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> survey of 200 housing professionals showed 75% believed materials, waste and other environmental issues in housing should be regulated.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">most </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at risk </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the responsible sourcing of materials and ecology and we urge that these are addressed by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Using the building regulations to specify responsible sourcing and include the Material section of the Code for Sustainable Homes</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Requiring ecological enhancement to be delivered through building regulations and biodiversity offsetting to contribute to the Government’s objective of securing net environmental gain</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We make a number of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">proposals for further change:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Strengthen the specification checklist for water use in appliances to require showers and water butts in every home and set higher standards for water efficiency and water use in showers</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Require provision of cycle storage for every home through building regulations</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Provide more consideration of overheating, the current methodology for which needs updating</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Combine the proposed minimum space standards across all tenures with a space labelling scheme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a benchmark</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Address the need for internal space for recycling through building regulations</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Develop the capability of the building control profession, including an extra accredited qualification in sustainability </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Introduce a new standard post 2016 for true zero carbon homes that goes beyond the current definition and includes current unregulated emissions</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Energy </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We welcome the restated commitment to ‘zero-carbon’ homes from 2016 and the proposal to mainstream this commitment by absorbing regulation of improved energy efficiency standards into building regulations.</span><ins><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></ins></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a serious risk, however, that slippage in bringing forward the new regulations and the significant gap between the scaled back 2013 regulations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will pose a challenge in meeting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the 2016 ‘zero carbon’ target. Allowable solutions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">help</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> industry to reach the 2016 standard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> however </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ambition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and commitment to training and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">zero carbon </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pilots</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will be needed in advance of the 2016 target</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e believe a standard beyond the current </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2016 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘zero-carbon’ definition needs to be developed that aims for true zero-carbon, including currently unregulated emissions.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Overheating</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">More serious consideration of overheating is needed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Overheating is acknowledged as a problem but the consultation does not offer serious consideration of this issue other than a proposal to keep it under review.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Curiously, the consultation states that “there are no standards or regulations that directly control overheating for thermal comfort”.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Yet, building regulations state that there should be a low risk of overheating and that this can be demonstrated using the methodology described in appendix P of SAP. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> existing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">requirements are in-fact already in need of review as the existing methodology</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> historic summer temperatures as part of its assessment and not projected temperatures, which could significantly alter the risk assessment.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Cycle storage</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposals to eliminate requirements for provision of cycle storage sit awkwardly with the Government’s clear commitment to encouraging more cycling. In responding to the All Party Parliamentary Cycling Group report </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Get Britain Cycling </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(2013)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Transport Minister Norman Baker said:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86.4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86.4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> “The coalition government takes cycling very seriously and we are committed to leading the country in getting more people cycling, more safely, more often”</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">4.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Storage is one of the practical barriers to further growth in cycling and we believe building regulations should support provision of secure cycle storage for each new home with the potential of local variation according to current and future demand.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Water</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposals seem a sensible approach.  We support the ability of and the capability for local authorities to impose a tighter minimum standard in areas of water scarcity although an alternative approach would be to establisher higher </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">effeiciency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> standards and allow these to be relaxed in areas of relative water surplus.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">5.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposal for a specification checklist of compliant flow rates for each fitting is very welcome.  It offers increased transparency and an outcomes based framework for builders which will allow for innovation and different approaches.  We believe the specification list could be improved in a number of areas:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Shower flow rate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: The shower flow rate in the suggested water specification should be amended from 10 to 8 litres per minute.  Research con</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ducted by Sustainable Homes for the London Climate Change Partnership (2013) has shown that low </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">flow </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">shower heads with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rates of 8 litres per minute </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">were acceptable to occupiers.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Showers should be a requirement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: If a specification list approach is used this should be clear that showers are required. Many, developers, particularly in social housing, do not install showers. If no shower is installed residents are likely bathe more often and therefore to use more water and energy. The Code’s whole house water use calculator account</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for this but the suggested specification list does not. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Water butts should be a requirement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: There is no proposed regulation or requirement to install water butts in homes with gardens, despite the relatively low cost.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is also an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">impotant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> consideration in adapting effectively to climate change</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Improved water efficiency levels</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Improved </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">building regulations should set </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">these </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at 105 litres per person per day: The consultation impact assessment shows that the cost difference between water efficiency standards of 125 litres and 105 litres per person per day are minimal and we know that Code 3 levels are already commonly in use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and working well</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Building regulations should incorporate th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">level as a default, with the option to vary allowances being available for areas where water is more plentiful. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Space standards</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Sustainable Homes welcome the inclusion of space standards in the consultation. These are currently unregulated through building regulations but assessed through HQIs. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; text-indent:-25.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6.1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The two options of a minimum space standard or a space labelling scheme are presented as mutually exclusive.  We support a hybrid approach which establishes minimum standards in building regulations across all tenures and then uses a space labelling scheme.  This will help prospective residents make informed decisions in choosing new homes which have larger rooms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Waste &amp; recycling</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">7.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposals on waste and recycling storage provision are confused and inconsistent.  There is welcome provision to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> strengthen requirements for external recycling space but too little attention to the implications of how recycling will be accommodated internall</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Internal recycling bins are mentioned in the design element of proposals for minimum space standards but not addressed in the proposals for space labelling. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">7.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A study by WRAP (2008) found that a lack of internal space for recycling is a significant barrier to household recycling.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nternal installation of space for recycling should be required under all options.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">7.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Space for internal recycling storage should be required in building regulations.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Omissions</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">8.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Sustainable Homes is seriously concerned </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the failure of the consultation document and the accompanying impact assessment to take account of the value accruing from broader sustainability and management considerations in housing standards.  These protect and contribute to wider environmental, social and health outcomes. This is a serious omission. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">8.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The following important considerations are currently included in standards but are omitted from the consultation: </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Home User Guides, </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Construction site impacts </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Considerate Constructors Schemes</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Materials</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Private outside space</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Flooding and rainwater runoff</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ecology</span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">8.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is no indication of how these benefits are to be provided under the new arrangements.  Sustainable Homes has received responses from approximately 200 housing professionals on their views on whether materials, waste and other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">environmental issues should be regulated in housing.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Around 75% of those asked stated that they believe they should be regulated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (Sustainable Homes, 2013)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">8.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">focus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> here on outlining practical ways that materials and ecology may be brought into a revised regulatory system.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Materials – responsible sourcing </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">9.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There may be a case for simplifying how responsible sourcing is demonstrated but omitting it altogether does not seem to be a reasonable response.  The consultation suggests that existing voluntary industry standards cover these areas and that regulation is therefore unnecessary. We do not agree. The voluntary standards mentioned in the consultation, including BS, ISO and CE, govern aspects of quality, design and processes but they do not cover the issues of embodied energy and environmental impacts of materials.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">9.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposals put at risk the key benefits from responsible sourcing – using materials which do not require human exploitation and encouraging greater use of recycled materials and reduced landfill.  The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uPVC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is one area where the benefits of greater recycling are evident and there is significant potential in growing this part of the green economy.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">9.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We suggest three policy options to encourage the use of more sustainable materials</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Include within building regulations specific requirements for sustainable sourcing. For example all timber used in construction is certified to FSC or equivalent standards. Similar certification standards might be required for other materials.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Include within building regulations an addendum to the BRE Green Guide, specifying that at least 80% building materials should be rated between A and D. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Absorb into building regulations the Materials sections of the Code for Sustainable Homes.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Ecology</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">10.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ecology is simply ignored in the consultation document.  This gross omission reinforces concerns raised by the Government’s Natural Capital Committee, that policies are too often based on economic rationalisation without reference to the value of our natural assets (2013). Ecological management in development processes are an important part of reversing a trend of biodiversity loss: populations of farmland and woodland species have declined by 28% and 17% respectively since 1990 (DEFRA, 2009). </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">10.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Biodiversity is crucial for a healthy ecosystem, upon which humans depend and it has important social and economic value.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The Government’s Natural Environment White Paper is unequivocal in recognising that:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Nature is sometimes taken for granted and undervalued. But people cannot flourish without the benefits and services our natural environment provides. Nature is a complex, interconnected system. A healthy, properly functioning natural environment is the foundation of sustained economic growth, prospering communities and personal wellbeing.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">This is why we must properly value the economic and social benefits of a healthy natural environment while continuing to recognise nature’s intrinsic value. The Government wants this to be the first generation to leave the natural environment of England in a better state than it inherited. To achieve so much means taking action across sectors rather than treating environmental concerns in isolation. It requires us all to put the value of nature at the heart of our decision-making – in Government, local communities and businesses. In this way we will improve the quality and increase the value of the natural environment across England.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">”</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">10.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">By omitting consideration of ecology the Housing Standards Review risks being an unfortunate example of taking nature for granted.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">10.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Housing development has a major impact on biodiversity.  As well as damaging and fragmenting existing habitats and ecosystems new development creates different opportunities for supporting wildlife.  The nation’s gardens are one of its most important wildlife resources and residents also benefit – whether through contact with nature in their back garden or the additional cooling effect of vegetation during increasingly extreme heat wave events.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nvironmental </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">benefits of biodiversity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have been estimated as valued in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">billions in health impacts alone</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK National Ecosystem Assessment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, 2011)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">10.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We suggest two policy options to encourage address biodiversity in new housing:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Explicitly link the H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ousing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tandards </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eview</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the Biodiversity Offsetting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">proposals currently being consulted on by Defra and the contribution which can be made through new development</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Incorporate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a requirement for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ecological enhancement within building regulations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to support delivery of the Government objective of “net environmental gain”</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Building control officer</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">11.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We support the focus on building control officers and approved bodies to implement the standards.  This will be a significantly expanded and more complex role and we have concerns about the capacity and expertise within current building control teams to deliver.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">11.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe the new approach to housing standards needs to be accompanied by a significant boost in the competency and status of the building control profession.  This needs to embrace sustainability as an important area for development.  Sustainability is a relatively new field with a wide variety of unregulated information from products and suppliers and this presents a challenge to building control departments.  We believe </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">there is a need for an extra accredited qualification for building control officers who will be approving the sustainability elements of building regulations as part of the review.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">References</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DEFRA (2009), “Sustainable development indicators in your pocket” available from </span><a href="http://collections.europarchive.org/tna/20090810002953/http://defra.gov.uk/sustainable/government/progress/data-resources/sdiyp.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://collections.europarchive.org/tna/20090810002953/http://defra.gov.uk/sustainable/government/progress/data-resources/sdiyp.htm</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin: